    oc:directiveContent "Do not use bodyweight values outside the defined clamp ranges: DOTS men 40–210 kg, DOTS women 40–150 kg; Wilks men 40–201.9 kg, Wilks women 26.51–154.53 kg; IPF GL requires bodyweight >= 35 kg. Values outside range silently map to boundary values." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Out-of-range weights are clamped, which may silently produce misleading scores if not caught." ;
    oc:severityLevel "HIGH" .

oc:kn_685ad013 a oc:Constraint,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When computing any powerlifting coefficient" ;
    oc:directiveContent "All bodyweight inputs must be in kilograms. Totals are the sum of squat, bench press, and deadlift in kilograms. Scores are undefined if bodyweight or total is zero." ;
    oc:hasRationale "The mathematical formulas depend on kg units; using pounds would produce incorrect scores." ;
    oc:severityLevel "CRITICAL" .

oc:kn_84255f51 a oc:KnowledgeNode,
        oc:Procedure ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When calculating any powerlifting score" ;
    oc:directiveContent "1. Determine which scoring system to use (DOTS, IPF GL, Wilks, or Glossbrenner). 2. Collect inputs: bodyweight (kg), total lifted (kg), sex (M/F/Mx), and for IPF GL also equipment (Raw/Single) and event (SBD/B). 3. Select the correct coefficient function based on sex (and equipment/event for IPF GL). 4. Compute coefficient, multiply by total to get points." ;
    oc:stepOrder 1 .

oc:kn_90b96082 a oc:DesignPrinciple,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When selecting or interpreting any powerlifting scoring system" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Each formula normalizes absolute strength by bodyweight using a gender-specific polynomial or exponential function, producing a dimensionless score that allows fair comparison across weight classes." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Heavier lifters have higher absolute totals, so without normalization lighter lifters cannot compete fairly." .

oc:kn_aa939cf5 a oc:Heuristic,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When choosing which scoring formula to apply" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Use DOTS for cross-sex team comparisons, IPF GL for IPF-sanctioned meets, Wilks for legacy/historical comparisons, and Glossbrenner for GPC-affiliate competitions." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Each federation and context has adopted a different standard; using the wrong formula yields non-comparable results." .

oc:kn_da544003 a oc:KnowledgeNode,
        oc:KnownIssue ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When deciding between Wilks and DOTS/IPF GL" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Wilks coefficient has been deprecated by the IPF in favor of IPF GL Points, which do not allow comparing between sexes. DOTS was created to fill this gap for mixed-sex team competitions." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Using Wilks in modern IPF contexts is incorrect; it remains useful for historical data comparison." .

oc:kn_e1037ae4 a oc:CodePattern,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When implementing any powerlifting scoring formula" ;
    oc:codeLanguage "rust" ;
    oc:directiveContent """Score = coefficient(bodyweight) × total
Coefficient = 500 / polynomial(a, b, c, d, e, bodyweight)  // for DOTS/Wilks
Coefficient = 100 / (A - B × e^(-C × bodyweight))  // for IPF GL""" .

